<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Mercury News File Photograph; NEW MOON -- Two images taken by
the satellite Voyager in 1989 show Proteus, the largest of six Neptunian moons
discovered during a satellite photo mission. The planet has eight known moons.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SPACE; RESEARCH; NAME  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Six moons of Neptune discovered by the Voyager 2 spacecraft in 1989 have been
named after water nymphs and the children and lovers of the mythological Greek
sea god Poseidon, an astronomy organization said Friday.;   A recently
discovered moon of Saturn was named Pan after the flute-playing Greek god of
fields and shepherds who was half man and half goat, the group said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  General News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ASTRONOMERS HAND OUT NAMES TO MOONS ORBITING 2
PLANETS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The planet <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> is named for the Roman god of the sea, known to the
ancient Greeks as Poseidon.;   Announcement by telegram; The six Neptunian
moons discovered by Voyager 2 were named <ORGANIZATION>Naiad</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Galatea</LOCATION>, both water nymphs;
Thalassa and <PERSON>Larissa</PERSON>, both lovers of <LOCATION>Poseidon</LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION>Proteus</ORGANIZATION>, one of the god's sons;
and <LOCATION>Despina</LOCATION>, a daughter.;   The names were revealed this week in a telegram
issued by the <ORGANIZATION>International Astronomical Union</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Central Bureau for
Astronomical Telegrams</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Cambridge</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, reporting agency for astronomy
discoveries.;   The <ORGANIZATION>IAU</ORGANIZATION>'s executive committee voted to approve the names when
it met <DATE>Aug. 2</DATE> in <LOCATION>Buenos Aires</LOCATION>, said astronomer <PERSON>Brian Marsden</PERSON>, the bureau's
director.;   Hidden in <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>'s rings; <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>'s newest moon, which the group
named Pan, was discovered hidden among the planet's rings by <PERSON>Mark Showalter</PERSON>, a
scientist at <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Ames Research Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Mountain View.</LOCATION>;   <PERSON>Showalter</PERSON> found
the 12-mile-wide moon <DATE>July 2, 1990</DATE>, when he was analyzing pictures of <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>
taken by Voyagers 1 and 2 when the twin spacecraft explored the planet in <DATE>1980</DATE>
and <DATE>1981.</DATE>;   Voyagers 1 and 2, laden with TV cameras and instruments, were
launched from <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> in <DATE>1977</DATE>. They visited <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE>. Voyager 2
explored Uranus in <DATE>1986</DATE> and <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> in <DATE>1989.</DATE>;   The two spacecraft discovered
at least 23 moons during their <MONEY>$865 million mission.</MONEY>;   <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> now has eight
known moons. Two were discovered from Earth-based telescopes. One, <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>,
named for a son of <LOCATION>Poseidon</LOCATION>, is <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s largest satellite, measuring 1,680
miles wide, and was discovered in <DATE>1846</DATE>. The other, <LOCATION>Nereid</LOCATION>, is 210 miles wide
and was discovered in <DATE>1949</DATE>. Naiad, the smallest of the newly discovered moons,
is 35 miles wide.;   <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> now has 18 known moons, 11 of which were
discovered by telescopes on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.  </TEXT>
