<HEAD>Fulbright Among Onassis Award Recipients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former <PERSON>Sen. J. William Fulbright</PERSON>, a team of
philologists and a Soviet museum are among this year's recipients of
the Onassis awards, worth <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> each, it was announced today.
   American physicist <PERSON>Amory B. Lovins</PERSON> and British doctor <PERSON>Dame Cicely
Saunders</PERSON> also will receive awards, the <ORGANIZATION>Alexander S. Onassis Public
Benefit Foudation</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The prizes honor international contributions in scholarship,
human rights and the environment.
   Premier <PERSON>Andreas Papandreou</PERSON> will present the awards <DATE>April 20</DATE> at a
ceremony in <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION>.
   Fulbright, 84, of <LOCATION>Arkansas</LOCATION>, will receive the Athinai prize for
``his major contribution to education by establishing this century's
largest international study fellowship program of academic and
cultural exchanges,'' said the foundation's president, Professor
<PERSON>Yannis Georgakis</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>Leningrad</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>State Hermitage Museum</ORGANIZATION>, cited for its archaeological
excavations along the Black Sea coast, will receive the Olympia
prize for its contribution to culture.
   <PERSON>Dame Cicely</PERSON>, who in <DATE>1961</DATE> founded the London-based <PERSON>St.
Christopher</PERSON>'s hospice for the terminally ill, will split the
Aristotelis prize for Man and Society with the <ORGANIZATION>Hellenic Spanish
Dictionary</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``We are honoring this dictionary for its important contribution
to the study and understanding of ancient Greek,'' said <PERSON>Georgakis</PERSON>.
   The Onassis prize for Man and His Environment goes to <PERSON>Lovins</PERSON>, 41,
for ``his notable contribution to the protection of the natural
environment by working towards alternative solutions to contemporary
energy problems,'' <PERSON>Georgakis</PERSON> said.
   In <DATE>1982</DATE> Lovins established the <ORGANIZATION>Colorado Rocky Mountain Institute</ORGANIZATION>,
which explores links between energy, water, agriculture and economic
development.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Onassis Foundation</ORGANIZATION> was set up in <DATE>1975</DATE> by the estate of Greek
shipping magnate <PERSON>Aristotle S. Onassis</PERSON> in honor of his son, who died
in a plane crash in <DATE>1973</DATE>.
</TEXT>
