<HEAD>Fulbright Gets Onassis Foundation Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> <PERSON>Sen. J. William Fulbright</PERSON> and
American physicist <PERSON>Amory B. Lovins</PERSON> were among those honored
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> with the annual Onassis prizes.
   Premier <PERSON>Andreas Papandreou</PERSON> gave out the awards, totaling
<MONEY>$400,000</MONEY>, at a ceremony in a packed chamber of the former
<ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> building.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Alexander S. Onassis Public Benefit Foundation</ORGANIZATION> presents the
prizes to honor international contributions in scholarship, human
rights and the environment.
   The main award, the Athinai prize, went to <LOCATION>Fulbright</LOCATION>, 84, for
establishing this century's largest international fellowship
program of academic and cultural exchanges.
   ``In the words of your tutor at <LOCATION>Oxford</LOCATION>, you are `responsible for
the largest and most signifcant movement of scholars across the
face of the earth since the fall of <LOCATION>Constantinople</LOCATION> in <DATE>1453</DATE>,''' <PERSON>John
Brademas</PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION>New York University</ORGANIZATION> told the <LOCATION>Arkansas</LOCATION>
Democrat as ministers, diplomats and local dignitaries looked on.
   Fulbright said he hoped the exchange progam he founded more than
40 years ago could play a role in ``enhancing mutual
understanding'' between countries.
   ``Through the international exchange program, I hope the young
people of the world will learn from one another ... if the outlook
for peace is as good as I think and pray it is, then these young
people will have the sort of world and future they are intended to
have,'' <PERSON>Fulbright</PERSON> said.
   <PERSON>Lovins</PERSON>, who in <DATE>1982</DATE> founded the <ORGANIZATION>Colorado Rocky Mountain
Institute</ORGANIZATION> that explores energy, water, agricultural security and
economic development, received the <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> Delphi Prize for Man
and His Environment.
   ``As <ORGANIZATION>Delphi</ORGANIZATION> is the navel of the ancient world, so energy is in a
sense the navel of modern society ... rediscovering our solar
rootstock, and grafting modern efficiency technologies onto it,
offers good news for all people and for the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON>Lovins</PERSON>,
41.
   Soviet professor <PERSON>Boris Piotrovsky</PERSON>, director of the
Leningrad-based <ORGANIZATION>Hermitage Museum</ORGANIZATION>, picked up the <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> Olympia
Prize for Man and Culture.
   The museum was honored for its discovery of several ancient
Greek cities along the Black Sea coast in its more than 150 years
of investigating the area.
   ``This award strengthens the bonds and cooperation that exist
between Soviet and Greek scientists involved in the history of the
ancient world,'' <PERSON>Piotrovsky</PERSON> said.
   The Aristotelis Prize for Man and Society went to both the
<ORGANIZATION>Hellenic Spanish Dictionary</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Dame Cicely Saunders</PERSON>, who
established the London-based <ORGANIZATION>St. Christopher</ORGANIZATION>'s Hospice for the
terminally ill in <DATE>1961</DATE>.
   The Spanish Hellenic Dictionary was honored for its contribution
to the study and understanding of ancient Greek. Spanish professor
<PERSON>Francisco Rodriguez Adrados</PERSON> accepted the award.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Onassis Foundation</ORGANIZATION> was set up in <DATE>1975</DATE> by the estate of the
late Greek shipping magnate <PERSON>Aristotle S. Onassis</PERSON> in memory of his
only son, who was killed in a plane crash in <DATE>1973</DATE>.
   Until <DATE>November 1988</DATE>, the philanthropic organization was headed
by <PERSON>Onassis</PERSON>' daughter, <PERSON>Christina</PERSON>. <PERSON>Ms. Onassis</PERSON>, 37, died <DATE>Nov. 19</DATE> of
an apparent heart attack in <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
