<H3> <TI>   Construction of Oil Pipeline to Greece Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Construction of Oil Pipeline to Greece Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2306095994 Sofia KONTINENT in Bulgarian 21 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU2306095994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia KONTINENT </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FP=106> [Unattributed report: "Oil Pipeline for <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> Through </F>
<LOCATION>Bulgaria</LOCATION> Planned"] 
  [Text] The construction of a Bulgarian-Greek oil pipeline 
from <LOCATION>Burgas</LOCATION> to the Aegean port of Alexandroupolis, an idea 
launched last month during the talks in <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> between Greek 
Foreign Minister <PERSON>Karolos Papoulias</PERSON> and Russian President <PERSON>Boris 
Yeltsin</PERSON>, will neutralize <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION>'s oil ambitions in the region. 
In addition, such a project will resolve the problem of 
transporting the Russian oil to <LOCATION>Western Europe</LOCATION>, the I 
KATHIMERINI Greek daily writes. 
  The oil pipeline, which will pass through southern <LOCATION>Bulgaria</LOCATION>, 
is also viewed as an opportunity to stop the expansionist 
strivings of <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> in the region, in which 1.5 million Muslims 
live, and strengthen security in <LOCATION>Thrace</LOCATION>, I KATHIMERINI writes. 
  Athens views the idea of constructing a Greek-Bulgarian oil 
pipeline from the Black Sea to the <ORGANIZATION>Aegean Sea</ORGANIZATION> as a counterpoint 
to the Turkish strategic plans aimed at establishing eventual 
control over the export of Russian oil. According to <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION>, 
<LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> also aims at establishing control over the oil of the 
former Soviet republics around the Caspian Sea. 
  By constructing the Greek-Bulgarian oil pipeline <LOCATION>Russia</LOCATION> 
would 
be able to free itself from its dependence on <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> and 
simultaneously, the strategic positions of <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Bulgaria</LOCATION> 
will be strengthened. 

</TEXT>

