<HEAD>Onassis' Body Arrives in Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of Greek shipping heiress
<PERSON>Christina Onassis</PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> today from <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> for burial
on her family's privately-owned island in the <LOCATION>Ionian Sea</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Ms. Onassis</PERSON>, 37, died in <PERSON>Buenos Aires</PERSON> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> of an apparent
heart attack, but the cause of death is still under investigation.
   Her body was flown to <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION> on a chartered <ORGANIZATION>Olympic Airways</ORGANIZATION>
aircraft from <LOCATION>Geneva</LOCATION> after it arrived on a regular <ORGANIZATION>Swissair</ORGANIZATION> flight
from <PERSON>Buenos Aires</PERSON>.
   Olympic was founded in <DATE>1957</DATE> by her father, shipping magnate
<PERSON>Aristotle Onassis</PERSON>, who then sold it to the Greek state in <DATE>1975</DATE>.
   Accompanying the body were a group of relatives and <PERSON>Ms. Onassis</PERSON>'
fourth ex-husband, French multimillionaire <PERSON>Thierry Roussel</PERSON>.
   A memorial service will be held for <PERSON>Ms. Onassis</PERSON> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> in the
Greek Orthodox church of Aghia Fotini in the <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION>Nea
Smyrni</LOCATION>.
   Ms <PERSON>Onassis</PERSON>' body will be flown to northwest <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> early <DATE>Saturday</DATE>
and then put aboard a launch for the short trip to the island of
Skorpios, where she will be buried next to her father and her
brother, <PERSON>Alexander</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Ms. Onassis</PERSON> inherited a fortune estimated at <MONEY>$500 million</MONEY> when
her father died in <DATE>1975</DATE>. The remainder of his <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> fortune was
given to the philanthropic <ORGANIZATION>Public Benefit Foundation</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
