<H3> <TI>   Government Warns Greece on Territorial Waters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Warns Greece on Territorial Waters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1605152294 Istanbul CUMHURIYET in Turkish 13 May 94 p 17 </F>
<F P=103> NC1605152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Istanbul CUMHURIYET </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FP=106> [Lale Sariibrahimoglu report: "Problem of 12-Mile </F>
Territorial Waters in the Aegean Sea"] 
  [Text] <LOCATION>Ankara</LOCATION>--The disagreement between <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> 
on <LOCATION>Athens</LOCATION>' intention to extend Greek territorial waters in the 
<LOCATION>Aegean Sea</LOCATION> to 12 miles has escalated as the time approaches for 
the Maritime Law Agreement to come into effect on 16 <DATE>November</DATE>. 
<ORGANIZATION>Greek Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> Spokesman <PERSON>Konstandinos Bikas</PERSON> said 
yesterday that <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION>'s approach to the matter has not changed. 
He also stressed that "extending the Greek territorial waters 
to 12 miles is a matter that concerns <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION>'s sovereign rights." 
  In a statement to CUMHURIYET, Greek diplomatic sources in 
<LOCATION>Ankara</LOCATION> have reiterated that extending Greek territorial waters 
to 12 miles is a matter of Greek sovereign rights. However, 
they also said: "<LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> does not intend to extend its 
territorial waters to 12 miles." 
  Replying to a question about a press report yesterday, 
<ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> Spokesman <PERSON>Ferhat Ataman</PERSON> has said that a move by 
<LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> to extend its territorial waters to 12 miles would be 
unacceptable. Meanwhile, a high-ranking <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> 
official informed CUMHURIYET that <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> would regard a move by 
<LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> to extend its territorial waters to 12 miles in 
contravention of international agreements as an act of war. 
  Turkey has reservations about various provisions of the 
<ORGANIZATION>Maritime Law Agreement</ORGANIZATION>, particularly Article 3. The agreement 
was signed in <DATE>1982</DATE> and has so far been ratified by 60 countries. 
According to that article, the signatory countries are 
authorized to extend their territorial waters up to 12 miles. 

</TEXT>

