<HEAD>Greece Will Take Part in One of Two Fall NATO Exercises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> will boycott autumn <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> maneuvers
in the Aegean Sea but will join another alliance exercise in
<LOCATION>Western Europe</LOCATION>, the government said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   ``According to the government's firm policy, Greek forces do not
take part in (<ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION>) exercises in the Aegean,'' said government
spokesman <PERSON>Sotiris Kostopoulos</PERSON>.
   He said <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> won't participate in the ``Display Determination
88'' maneuvers in the eastern <LOCATION>Mediterranean</LOCATION> this <DATE>fall</DATE>.
   But <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> will take part in the ``Autumn Forge 88'' exercises
since ``our armed forces do participate from time to time in
bilateral and multilateral technical exercises on a smaller scale
being carried out outside the Aegean,'' <PERSON>Kostopoulos</PERSON> said.
   Since <DATE>1981</DATE>, <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> has refused to participate in <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> exercises
in the Aegean, saying the alliance favors <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> by excluding the
Greek island of Lemnos from the exercise scenarios.
   Turkey claims that Lemnos should not be militarized, citing the
<DATE>1923</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Lausanne Treaty</ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> maintains the <DATE>1936</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Montreux Convention</ORGANIZATION>
superseded the earlier treaty and allows military installations on
the northern Aegean island.
   <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Turkey</LOCATION> have a long feud over military control of the
Aegean Sea region.
</TEXT>
